'''Amarar''' (or Amarer) is a [[bedouin]] tribe of the [[Beja people]] inhabiting the mountainous country on the west side of the [[Red Sea]] from [[Suakin]] northwards towards [[Al-Qusayr, Egypt|Al-Qusayr]]. Between them and the [[Nile]] are the [[Ababda]] and [[Bisharin]] Beja tribes and to their south dwell the [[Hadendoa]] (another Beja subgroup).<ref name="At war with Bisharin">{{cite book|last1=Burckhardt|first1=John Lewis|title=Travels in Nubia: by the late John Lewis Burckhardt|date=1819|publisher=Association for Promoting the Discovery of the Interior Parts of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vE4GAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref> The country of the Amarar is called the [[Atbai]]. Their headquarters are in the [[Ariab]] district. The tribe is divided into four great families: (1) [[Weled Gwilei]], (2) [[Weled Aliab]], (3) [[Weled Kurbab Wagadab]], and (4) the Amarar proper of the Ariab district. They claim to be of [[Quraysh (tribe)|Koreish]] blood and to be the descendants of an invading Arab army. Possibly some small bands of Koreish Arabs may have made an inroad and converted some of the Amarar to [[Islam]]. Further than this there is little to substantiate their claim.<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Amarar|volume=1|page=781}} This cites: * ''Anglo-Egyptian Sudan'', edited by [Lord Edward Gleichen|Count Gleichen]] (London, 1905) * Sir F. R. Wingate, ''Mahdism and the Egyptian Sudan'' (London, 1891) * [[Augustus Henry Keane|A. H. Keane]], ''Ethnology of Egyptian Sudan'' (London, 1884).</ref>
